luding the Balkans, the Maghreb, and West Africa who decided to sell sex as the means to achieve a better life. Mai explores the contrast between how migrants understand themselves and their work and how humanitarian and governmental agencies conceal their stories, often unwittingly, by addressing them all as helpless victims. The culmination of two decades of research, Mobile Orientations sheds new light on the desires and ambitions of migrant sex workers across the world.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aForeign workerszEurope. 0aHuman traffickingzEurope. 0aMale prostituteszEurope. 0aMale prostitutionzEurope. 0aProstitutionzEurope. 0aSex workerszEurope. 0aSexual orientationzEurope. 4aParticipatory methods. 4aagency. 4aautoethnography. 4afilmmaking. 4ahumanitarianism. 4amigration. 4aneoliberalism. 4asex work. 4atrafficking. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226585147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226585147.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles